article.description:
Lisa Leslie scored 26 points and made the
game-winning free throw to lift the Los Angeles Sparks to a 82-81 win over the Seattle Storm on Friday night.
article.headline: Leslie's 26 points help Sparks edge Storm
article.linkText: Leslie gives L.A. extra Spark to top Storm
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Lisa Leslie won the game at the free-throw
line after Los Angeles teammate Tamecka Dixon was ejected following
a scuffle.

Leslie scored 26 points Friday night to lift the Sparks to a
82-81 win over the Seattle Storm.

With the game winding down and the Sparks holding onto an 81-77
lead, Dixon and Storm guard Betty Lennox scrambled for a loose
ball. The two bumped and swapped words. Dixon then took a swipe at
Lennox.

Dixon, who had 20 points, received a double-technical and was
ejected with 1:34 remaining.

"Just trash talking," Lennox said. "I know no blows touched
me. I protected myself and focused on the next play."

After Dixon's ejection, Seattle scored four straight to tie the
game at 81 with 30.6 seconds left.

Leslie's free throw came with 10.5 seconds remaining, and Sue
Bird missed an off-balance shot in the final seconds.

"Even though we lost Tamecka, we persevered and showed a lot of
heart," Leslie said. "It was definitely a lot more physical, and
a lot of people weren't happy about it."

Los Angeles (21-7) has won seven straight, and extended its lead
over the second-place Storm to 3½ games in the Western Conference.

Nikki Teasley had 14 points for the Sparks, making four
3-pointers.

Bird had 25 points for Seattle (17-10). Lennox finished with 18
points and Kamila Vodichkova added 17.

Bird connected on 9-of-11 shots, including 5-for-6 from behind
the arc.

In the second half, the Storm took a 60-59 lead with 11:32
remaining. The Sparks pulled ahead on a 11-2 run.

Los Angeles shot 57 percent overall and won the points in the
paint, 40-30. Seattle outrebounded the Sparks, 35-25.

Both teams had solid 3-point shooting, the Storm making 8-of-13
and the Sparks going 5-of-11.

Seattle played without WNBA leading scorer Lauren Jackson
(20.6), who is in Australia with her ill grandmother.

Jackson, who is resting an injured foot, is not expected to
rejoin the team until Wednesday against Detroit.
